
 File: man_1_simple_shell

```man
.TH HSH 18 "December 2025" "Holberton School" "Simple Shell Manual"

.SH NAME

hsh \- simple UNIX command interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh

.SH DESCRIPTION
hsh is a minimal UNIX command interpreter written in C.
It behaves similarly to /bin/sh and supports both interactive
and non-interactive modes.

The shell reads commands from standard input, parses them,
and executes them using fork and execve.

.SH USAGE
Interactive mode:
.IP
./hsh

Non-interactive mode:
.IP
echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh

.SH FEATURES
.IP \[bu] 2
Displays a prompt ($) in interactive mode
.IP \[bu]
Executes commands with arguments
.IP \[bu]
Searches commands using the PATH environment variable
.IP \[bu]
Does not call fork() when a command is not found
.IP \[bu]
Handles empty or missing PATH and empty environments
.IP \[bu]
Implements built-in commands: exit and env

.SH BUILTINS
.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell using the last command's exit status.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment variables.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
The shell uses the PATH environment variable to locate executable files.
Environment variables are accessed without using getenv().

.SH EXIT STATUS
.IP \[bu] 2
0 on success
.IP \[bu]
127 if the command is not found
.IP \[bu]
Other values correspond to child process exit status

.SH ERRORS
When a command is not found, hsh prints a UNIX-compliant error message:
.IP
./hsh: 1: command: not found

.SH CONSTRAINTS
.IP \[bu] 2
No forbidden functions used
.IP \[bu]
No system()
.IP \[bu]
No getenv()
.IP \[bu]
No dprintf()
.IP \[bu]
No printf() for error messages
.IP \[bu]
ISO C90 compliant
.IP \[bu]
Betty style compliant
.IP \[bu]
No memory leaks (checked with Valgrind)

.SH SEE ALSO
sh(1), bash(1)

.SH AUTHOR
James Roussel and Maxime RÃ©gnier, Holberton School students.
 
